<font color="#FF0000">PAY THE PRICE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 22  1:55:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
When an American goes to visit the Wall he or she finds out what the &quot;price&quot; is.  It really doesn't matter if you are a combat veteran or not when it comes to the &quot;price&quot;.  At the Wall we acknowledge that those our fallen comrades paid the &quot;price&quot;-since they paid all that they possibly could pay.  And when we leave the Wall we feel relief at our returning emotional composure.  But, it is necessary to come to grip personally with what the &quot;price&quot; really is and who must pay it.  In your heart you know that the price is everything you have.  You also know that a lesser payment will not do.  I don't think so.  And so we all understand that if we really want to accomplish that something of vital importance whatever it was or may be we should be reconciled to the &quot;price&quot; that is called for.  As Nam vets we came close, very close to paying that &quot;price&quot;.  So even if many of us have not consciously thought of it still we know what that &quot;price&quot; entails.  I feel this understanding about the cost of what is dear is vital to our nation.  It takes on a sacred texture and because of the reality of it transcends petty squabbles of various kinds.  Obviously, we share this with others just because of who we are.  However, what each of us finally realizes as we gaze with wonder on love ones near is that we too have to pay that &quot;price&quot;.  Our friends on the Wall look expectantly our way waiting.  When we were young our elders told us what to pay that &quot;price&quot; for.  But now we are the elders.  All the eyes are turning to us.  Choose well therefore.  What say you?  If we pass on our experiences, impressions, passions, fears, trusts, hopes and all else we have gained as a result of almost giving our lives in Nam, still it will not be enough.  Only the &quot;price&quot; will ever be enough.  For our friends/comrades who died in Nam it was enough so that we have stood with them through disrepute and all the rest down through the years.  They reside safely in our hearts even now.  Only the &quot;price&quot; is enough.  And possibly only those of us who have suffered as a result of our nations armed conflicts can tell others what the &quot;price&quot; really is.  
